s=3D"mw-disambig" title=3D"Lye (disambiguation)">Lye (disambiguation)</a>.<=
/div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:HK_TKO_%E5%B0%87%E8%BB%8D%E6%BE%B3%E5%BB%A3%E=
5%A0%B4_Tseung_Kwan_O_Plaza_mall_shop_JHC_%E6%97%A5%E6%9C%AC%E5%9F%8E_Japan=
_Home_Centre_goods_June_2019_SSG_02.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img=
 src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/HK_TKO_%E=
5%B0%87%E8%BB%8D%E6%BE%B3%E5%BB%A3%E5%A0%B4_Tseung_Kwan_O_Plaza_mall_shop_J=
HC_%E6%97%A5%E6%9C%AC%E5%9F%8E_Japan_Home_Centre_goods_June_2019_SSG_02.jpg=
/250px-HK_TKO_%E5%B0%87%E8%BB%8D%E6%BE%B3%E5%BB%A3%E5%A0%B4_Tseung_Kwan_O_P=
laza_mall_shop_JHC_%E6%97%A5%E6%9C%AC%E5%9F%8E_Japan_Home_Centre_goods_June=
_2019_SSG_02.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"=
mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"3264" data-file-height=3D"2448"></a><fi=
gcaption>Lye for sale in a shop in Hong Kong</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Lye</b> is the common name of various <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Alkaline" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Alkaline">alkaline</a> s=
olutions, including <b>soda lye</b> (a solution of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Sodium_hydroxide" title=3D"Sodium hydroxide">sodium hydrox=
ide</a>) and <b>potash lye</b> (a solution of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Potassium_hydroxide" title=3D"Potassium hydroxide">potassium hy=
droxide</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-2">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> Lyes are used as cleaning products, as ingredients in soapmaking=
, and in various other contexts.=20
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLye&amp;action=3Dedit&=
amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span></a><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The word <i lang=3D"en"><a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/lye#En=
glish" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:lye">lye</a></i> derives from the Germ=
anic root *<i>lau</i>, meaning "to wash" (compare <i lang=3D"en"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/lave#English" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt=
:lave">lave</a></i>, <i lang=3D"en"><a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wi=
ki/lather#English" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:lather">lather</a></i>) an=
d has <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognates" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Cognates">cognates</a> in all the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Germanic_languages" title=3D"Germanic languages">Germanic lang=
uages</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The word could appear in old=
er English texts as <i>ley</i>.
</p><p>Traditional lye-makers leached <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Wood_ash" title=3D"Wood ash">wood ashes</a> in water, producing an alka=
line liquor rich in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Potassium_carb=
onate" title=3D"Potassium carbonate">potassium carbonate</a> or potash. Add=
ing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slaked_lime" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Slaked lime">slaked lime</a> could increased the alkalinity, =
causing the solute to become potassium hydroxide or caustic potash.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Lye#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Uses">Uses</h2><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLye&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;=
section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Uses"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Food">Food</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLye&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;=
section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Food"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Preparing_for_Christmas_1950_(JOKAMT2Kot06-4)=
.tif" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.or=
g/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Preparing_for_Christmas_1950_%28JOKAMT2Kot06=
-4%29.tif/lossy-page1-250px-Preparing_for_Christmas_1950_%28JOKAMT2Kot06-4%=
29.tif.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"387" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-element" data-file-width=3D"2953" data-file-height=3D"4576"></a><figcapti=
on>A Finnish woman preparing a <i>lutefisk</i> or lye-cured fish</figcaptio=
n></figure>
<p>Lyes are used to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curing_(food_p=
reservation)" title=3D"Curing (food preservation)">cure</a> many types of f=
ood, including olives and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dutch_pr=
ocess_cocoa" title=3D"Dutch process cocoa">cocoa</a> (making them less bitt=
er), canned <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mandarin_orange" title=
=3D"Mandarin orange">mandarin oranges</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Lye_roll" title=3D"Lye roll">lye rolls</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Century_egg" title=3D"Century egg">century eggs</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pretzel" title=3D"Pretzel">pretzels</=
a>, candied pumpkins, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bagel" t=
itle=3D"Bagel">bagels</a>.
</p><p>Lye is the curing agent and namesake of the traditional Nordic <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lutefisk" title=3D"Lutefisk">lutefisk</=
a>, a type of preserved fish. They are also used as a tenderizer in the cru=
st of baked Cantonese <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mooncake" ti=
tle=3D"Mooncake">moon cakes</a>, in "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Zongzi" title=3D"Zongzi">zongzi</a>" (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Glutinous_rice" title=3D"Glutinous rice">glutinous rice</a> dumpling=
s wrapped in bamboo leaves), in chewy southern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Chinese_noodles" title=3D"Chinese noodles">Chinese noodles</a>=
 popular in Hong Kong and southern China, and in Japanese <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramen_noodles" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ramen=
 noodles">ramen noodles</a>. In the Philippines, lye is used in the making =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kutsinta" title=3D"Kutsinta">ku=
tsinta</a>, a type of rice cake, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Pitsi-pits%C3%AE" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pitsi-pits=C3=AE">pitsi=
-pits=C3=AE</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-philrice_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-philrice-6"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assam" title=3D"Assam">Assam</a=
>, extensive use is made of a type of lye called <i>khar</i> in Assamese an=
d <i>karwi</i> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boro_language_(I=
ndia)" title=3D"Boro language (India)">Boro</a>, which is obtained from the=
 ashes of banana stems, roots, and skins. It is used in cooking, curing, as=
 medicine, and as a substitute for soap. Lye made out of wood ashes is also=
 used in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nixtamalization" titl=
e=3D"Nixtamalization">nixtamalization</a> process of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Hominy" title=3D"Hominy">hominy</a> corn by the tribes o=
f the Eastern Woodlands in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_A=
merica" title=3D"North America">North America</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Homin=
y_Foodway_of_the_Historic_Native_Eastern_Woodland_7-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-Hominy_Foodway_of_th=
e_Historic_Native_Eastern_Woodland-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Chocolate was first <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dutch_process_cocoa" title=3D"Dutch proc=
ess cocoa">dutched</a> using lye as a way to alkalize the cacao bean. <sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Lye#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States" title=
=3D"United States">United States</a>, food-grade lye must meet the requirem=
ents outlined in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Food_Chemical=
s_Codex" title=3D"Food Chemicals Codex">Food Chemicals Codex</a>,<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L=
ye#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> as prescribed by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Food_and_Drug_Administration" title=3D"Food and Drug Administ=
ration">Food and Drug Administration</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FDA_10-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-FDA-=
10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Lower grades of lye that are unsuitable for use in food pre=
paration are commonly used as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drai=
n_cleaner" title=3D"Drain cleaner">drain cleaners</a> and oven cleaners.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-FDA_10-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-FDA-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-=
Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citing sources"><spa=
n title=3D"This citation requires a reference to the specific page or range=
 of pages in which the material appears. (November 2014)">page&nbsp;needed<=
/span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Soap">Soap</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLye&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;=
section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Soap"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Both sodium hydroxide and potassium hydroxide are used in making <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soap" title=3D"Soap">soap</a>. Potassium =
hydroxide soaps are softer and more easily dissolved in water than sodium h=
ydroxide soaps. Sodium hydroxide and potassium hydroxide are not interchang=
eable in either the proportions required or the properties produced in maki=
ng soaps.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"whit=
e-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Cit=
ation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim=
 needs references to reliable sources. (October 2024)">citation needed</spa=
n></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>"Hot process" soap making also uses lye as the main ingredient. Lye =
is added to water, cooled for a few minutes and then added to oils and butt=
ers. The mixture is then cooked over a period of time (1=E2=80=932 hours), =
typically in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slow_cooker" title=
=3D"Slow cooker">slow cooker</a>, and then placed into a mold.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Beauty">Beauty</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLye&amp;action=3Dedit&am=
p;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Beauty"><span>edit</span></a><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Lye, like other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydroxide" titl=
e=3D"Hydroxide">hydroxide</a>-based products, is also used as a hair <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relaxer" title=3D"Relaxer">relaxer</a> a=
nd straightener. Lye relaxers break a third of the chemical bonds in the ha=
ir strand and cause the hair to swell. Rinsing and then heating the hair st=
raightens the strands.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Due to thei=
r high <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PH" title=3D"PH">pH</a>, th=
ey often cause scalp irritation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Lye#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Though no-lye solutions, which use <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guanidine" title=3D"Guanidine">guanid=
ine</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lithium_hydroxide" titl=
e=3D"Lithium hydroxide">lithium hydroxide</a>, produce less scalp irritatio=
n, they may cause brittleness due to calcium deposits.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_no=
te-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>People of African descent have used lye to relax or straighten hair =
since the nineteenth century.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Black =
men used lye-based formulations to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Conk" title=3D"Conk">conk</a> their hair, and black entrepreneurs sold suc=
h formulations under names like Konkalene; <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/The_Autobiography_of_Malcolm_X" title=3D"The Autobiography of Malc=
olm X">The Autobiography of Malcolm X</a> includes an account of Malcolm X =
receiving his first lye conk.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnson_Products_Company" title=3D"J=
ohnson Products Company">Johnson Products Company</a> introduced industrial=
ly produced lye-based relaxers for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Category:African-American_hair" title=3D"Category:African-American hair">A=
frican American salon hair care</a> in the 1950s; Ultra Wave was marketed t=
o men and Ultra Sheen was marketed to women, and the company represented 80=
% of the chemical relaxer market through the 1960s. In 1971, Johnson Produc=
ts became the first black-owned company on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/American_Stock_Exchange" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Americ=
an Stock Exchange">American Stock Exchange</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-17">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Industrial">Industrial</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLye&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Industrial"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A number of alkaline substance including sodium hydroxide have been used=
 to adjust the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PH" title=3D"PH">pH=
</a> during factory processes. It is regularly used to make fruit juices al=
kaline so that the pulp and sediment will clump, or form <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flocculation" title=3D"Flocculation">flocs</a>, and =
can be removed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This results in a cl=
ear fruit juice that has been clarified. Due to low cost, it has been the m=
ain way that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalding" title=3D"Sc=
alding">chicken scalding tanks</a> are kept sanitary, with an added benefit=
 that it helps the feathers come off.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-19"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Household">Household</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLye&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Household"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Lejia_de_ceniza.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descrip=
tion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd=
/Lejia_de_ceniza.jpg/250px-Lejia_de_ceniza.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"245" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1536" dat=
a-file-height=3D"1508"></a><figcaption>A jar of homemade wood ash lye</figc=
aption></figure>
<p>Lyes are also valued for their cleaning effects. Sodium hydroxide is com=
monly the major constituent in commercial and industrial <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cleaning_agent" title=3D"Cleaning agent">oven cleane=
rs</a> and clogged <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemical_drain_=
cleaners#Alkaline_drain_openers" title=3D"Chemical drain cleaners">drain op=
eners</a>, due to its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fat" title=
=3D"Fat">grease</a>-dissolving abilities. Lyes decompose greases via <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ester_hydrolysis" title=3D"Ester hydroly=
sis">alkaline ester hydrolysis</a>, yielding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Water-soluble" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Water-soluble">wat=
er-soluble</a> residues that are easily removed by rinsing.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Tissue_digestion">Tissue di=
gestion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLye&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Tissue digestion"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>Sodium or potassium hydroxide can be used to digest tissues of animal ca=
rcasses. Often referred to as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alka=
line_hydrolysis_(death_custom)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Alkaline hyd=
rolysis (death custom)">alkaline hydrolysis</a>, the process involves placi=
ng the animal carcass into a sealed chamber, adding a mixture of lye and wa=
ter and the application of heat to accelerate the process. After several ho=
urs the chamber will contain a liquid with coffee-like appearance,<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Ayres_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-Ayres-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-carcassdi=
sposal_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L=
ye#cite_note-carcassdisposal-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-22"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> and the only solids that remain are very fragile bone hulls of m=
ostly <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calcium_phosphate" title=3D"=
Calcium phosphate">calcium phosphate</a>, which can be mechanically crushed=
 to a fine powder with very little force.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-23"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Roach_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-Roach-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Sodium hydroxide=
 is frequently used in the process of decomposing <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Roadkill" title=3D"Roadkill">roadkill</a> dumped in landfil=
ls by animal disposal contractors.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-carcassdisposal_21-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note=
-carcassdisposal-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Due to its low cost and easy availability,=
 it has also been used to dispose of corpses by criminals. <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italy" title=3D"Italy">Italian</a> <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serial_killer" title=3D"Serial killer">serial kil=
ler</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonarda_Cianciulli" title=
=3D"Leonarda Cianciulli">Leonarda Cianciulli</a> used this chemical to turn=
 dead bodies into soap.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In Mexico, =
a man who worked for drug cartels admitted to having disposed of more than =
300 bodies with it.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lye#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fungus_identification">Fung=
us identification</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DLye&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Fungus =
identification"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemical_test_in_mus=
hroom_identification" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chemical test in mushr=
oom identification">Chemical test in mushroom identification</a></div>
<p>A 3=E2=80=9310% solution of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pot=
assium_hydroxide" title=3D"Potassium hydroxide">potassium hydroxide</a> (KO=
H) gives a color change in some species of mushrooms:
</p>
<ul><li>In <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agaricus" title=3D"A=
garicus">Agaricus</a></i>, some species such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Agaricus_xanthodermus" title=3D"Agaricus xanthodermus">A. xan=
thodermus</a> turn yellow with KOH, many have no reaction, and <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agaricus_subrutilescens" title=3D"Agaricu=
s subrutilescens">A. subrutilescens</a></i> turns green.</li>
<li>Distinctive change occurs for some species of <i><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Cortinarius" title=3D"Cortinarius">Cortinarius</a></i> a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boletes" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Boletes">boletes</a></li></ul>
