<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"First_aid">First aid</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLye&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: First aid"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>When a person has been exposed to lye, sources recommend immediate remov=
al of contaminated clothing/materials, gently brushing/wiping excess off of=
 skin, and then flushing the area of exposure with running water for 15=E2=
=80=9360 minutes as well as contacting emergency services.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-CCOHS_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Lye#cite_note-CCOHS-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Protection">Protection</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLye&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Protection"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Personal_protective_equipment" =
title=3D"Personal protective equipment">Personal protective equipment</a> i=
ncluding safety glasses, chemical-resistant gloves, and adequate ventilatio=
n are required for the safe handling of lye. When in proximity to lye that =
is dissolving in an open container of water, the use of a vapor-resistant f=
ace mask is recommended. Adding lye too quickly can cause a runaway thermal=
 reaction which can result in the mixture boiling or erupting.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Storage">Storage</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLye&amp;action=3Dedit&=
amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Storage"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Lye in its solid state is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deliq=
uescent" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Deliquescent">deliquescent</a> and =
has a strong affinity for moisture in the air. As a result, lye will dissol=
ve when exposed to open air, absorbing large amounts of atmospheric moistur=
e. Accordingly, lye is stored in air-tight (and correspondingly moisture ti=
ght) containers. Glass is not a good material to be used for storage as sev=
ere alkalis are mildly corrosive to it. Similar to the case of other corros=
ives, the containers should be labeled to indicate the potential danger of =
the contents and stored away from children, pets, heat, and moisture.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Hazardous_reactions">Hazard=
ous reactions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DLye&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Hazardous=
 reactions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>The majority of safety concerns with lye are also common with most corro=
sives, such as their potentially destructive effects on <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tissue_(biology)" title=3D"Tissue (biology)">living t=
issues</a>; examples are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skin"=
 title=3D"Skin">skin</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flesh" t=
itle=3D"Flesh">flesh</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Cornea" title=3D"Cornea">cornea</a>. Solutions containing lyes can cause <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemical_burn" title=3D"Chemical bur=
n">chemical burns</a>, permanent injuries, scarring and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blindness" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Blindness">=
blindness</a>, immediately upon contact. Lyes may be harmful or even fatal =
if swallowed; ingestion can cause <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Esophageal_stricture" title=3D"Esophageal stricture">esophageal stricture</=
a>. Moreover, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solvation" title=
=3D"Solvation">solvation</a> of dry <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Solid" title=3D"Solid">solid</a> lye is highly <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Exothermic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Exothermic">exoth=
ermic</a> and the resulting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heat" =
title=3D"Heat">heat</a> may cause additional burns or ignite flammables.
</p><p>The reaction between sodium hydroxide and some metals is also hazard=
ous. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aluminium" title=3D"Aluminium=
">Aluminium</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnesium" title=
=3D"Magnesium">magnesium</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zinc=
" title=3D"Zinc">zinc</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tin" ti=
tle=3D"Tin">tin</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromium" tit=
le=3D"Chromium">chromium</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bras=
s" title=3D"Brass">brass</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
ronze" title=3D"Bronze">bronze</a> all react with lye to produce <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrogen" title=3D"Hydrogen">hydrogen</a> ga=
s. Since hydrogen is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flammable" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Flammable">flammable</a>, mixing a large quant=
ity of lye with aluminium could result in an explosion. Both the potassium =
and sodium forms are able to dissolve copper.
